{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}} {{Use British English|date=February 2016}} {{Infobox cricketer | name = Bartram | image = | country = England | fullname = unknown | nickname = | birth_date = c.1715 | birth_place = [[England]] | batting = unknown hand | bowling = underarm: unknown hand and type | role = batsman | club1 = [[Kent county cricket teams|Kent]] | year1 = c.1735–1755 | club2 = | year2 = | date = 8 February | year = 2013 | columns = 0 | source = [[Arthur Haygarth]] }}
'''Bartram''' (first name and dates unknown) was an English [[cricket]]er who played in [[first-class cricket|first-class]] matches for [[Kent county cricket teams|Kent]] during the 1740s. He is recorded in cricket's second-oldest surviving scorecard playing for Kent against an [[All-England Eleven]] at the [[Artillery Ground]] on Monday, 18 June 1744. He scored two [[run (cricket)|runs]] and held one catch. Kent won by 1 wicket.<ref>Haygarth, p.1.</ref>
As Bartram had established his reputation by 1744, he must have been active for some years previously and his career probably began in the 1730s. Very few players were mentioned by name in contemporary reports and there are no other references to Bartram.
